performed after the neutron irradiations. For the 109Pd

- Description of
HFBR
For thermal capture, the absolute intensity of the
strongest primary gamma-ray in 109Pd (Eg=4794.0 keV)
was determined to be 68.3 +- 7.8 photons/1000 neutron
captures, which is in disagrement with value of
30.0 photons/1000 neutron captures derived from
measurements of Rasmussen+ based on thermal capture
cross section of 6.1 +-0.4 and 8.3 +-0.8 b (from
private comm. with J.E.Rambak and E.Steinnes)
respectively, for Pd and 108Pd.

- reference to the
88.034 keV 109Ag line.
The GAMS data were energy calibrated internally by
demanding that a line have the same energy in all
orders of reflection in which it is observed. Absolute
energy calibration is performed by reference to the
88.034 keV 109Ag line.
Since the GAMS target is viewed end on by the
spectrometers, the self-absorption corrections can be
large. For this reason the adopted intensities for the
low energy gamma-rays were obtained by plotting the
ratio of Ge(Li) intensities to those measured by the
GAMS spectrometers, and by using the values for strong
transitions to define a relative effective GAMS
efficiency curve (including automatically the
self-absorption correction) and by using this curve to
normalize all GAMS intensities to the Ge(Li) intensity
scale.
The observed gamma-ray energies are obtained from the
curved-crystal spectrometer experiments.
description of GAMS
At BNL the target consisted of 5.52 grams enriched to
98.11% in 108Pd and formed into a rectangle
approximately 2.54 cm x 2.86 cm.
At ILL the target was an in-pile laminar sample of
~70 mg of enriched 108Pd
